<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Desktop Computer" class="currentChild" href="Desktop_Computer">Desktop Computer</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
Any small, <a title="Microcomputer" href="Microcomputer">microcomputer</a> that can literally fit on a desk, as opposed to a <a title="Mainframe" href="Mainframe">mainframe</a>, which typically requires its own room. A desktop computer is essentially a compact unit consisting of a case containing the computer itself, including the <a title="CPU" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/CPU">CPU</a> and other chips controlling all the peripherals that can be attached to the computer, as well as a hard disk drive, one or more floppy disk drives, and, increasingly, internal CD-ROM drives and modems. A monitor, a keyboard, and a mouse are also attached to the system. 
</p>
